  "diary": "Sunday felt like a gift—the kind of day where everything just flows. Started with my usual ritual: pour-over coffee and the morning light streaming through the kitchen window. The ride to Green Lake was perfect, crisp air, hardly anyone around yet. I jogged the loop twice, feeling strong.\n\nAfter cleaning up, I spent a couple hours with my knitting and a podcast about design history. Something about the repetitive motion and storytelling just settles me. Wandered down to Wallingford Center for lunch—grabbed a coffee and ended up at Molly Moon's for a late brunch. The neighborhood was buzzing but not frantic.\n\nPickup basketball at the playfield this afternoon was exactly what I needed. Nothing serious, just some neighbors shooting around. My legs are going to feel that tomorrow. The rest of the evening dissolved into more knitting, tea, and just... being. No deadlines, no Slack notifications. Ended the day journaling on the couch as the light faded. Feeling rested in a way I haven't in weeks.",
  "thought_process": "I think I needed this kind of day more than I realized. Work's been grinding lately—lots of stakeholder feedback, design iterations that never quite land. The gorgeous weather pulled me outside early, and I leaned into that momentum instead of fighting it. Knitting has become my anchor lately; it's meditative in a way that scrolling never is. I chose to stay local, stay in Wallingford, because the idea of navigating crowds or traffic felt exhausting. Basketball was spontaneous—I almost talked myself out of it, but my body needed to move hard, not just gently. By evening I was genuinely tired and content, which is rare. The calm Sunday meant no external pressure, so I could just... exist. That made all the difference.",
